: Calculate, for the normal distributed variable <em>V</em>the average &mu; when:<br />$P(V &ge; $g<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = <b>?</b>  and &sigma; = $sigma) = $[1-$kans] 
: <ul><li>$P(V &ge; $g<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = <b>?</b>  and &sigma; = $sigma) = $[1-$kans]</li><li>$P(V &lt; $g<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = <b>?</b>  and &sigma; = $sigma) = $kans</li><li>input for  a TexasInstruments Ti83 &trade; graphical calculator <kbd>invNorm</kbd>($kans) ; That will give you the z-value</li><li>&mu; = $g - z * $sigma</li><li>&mu; = $g - $Z*$sigma</li><li>SoĀthe average is: $mean</li></ul>
: <ul><li>$P(V &ge; $g<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = <b>?</b>  and &sigma; = $sigma) = $[1-$kans]</li><li>$P(V &lt; $g<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = <b>?</b>  and &sigma; = $sigma) = $kans</li><li>Lookup in your table the probability closest to $kans </li><li>That should be $kans1</li><li>The corresponding z=$Z1</li><li>Use the formula z=(g - &mu; )/ &sigma; </li><li>So $Z1 = ($g - &mu;)/$sigma</li><li>Then $Z1*$sigma = $g - &mu;</li><li>So $[$Z1*$sigma]=$g-&mu;</li><li>So the average (mean) = $mean</li></ul>
: Calculate, for the normal distributed variable <em>V</em> the standard deviation &sigma; when:<br />$P(V &le; $g<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = $mean and &sigma; = <b>?</b> ) = $kans 
: <ul><li>$P(V &le; $g<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = $mean and &sigma; = <b>?</b> ) = $kans</li><li>input for a TexasInstruments Ti83 &trade; graphical calculator <kbd>invNorm</kbd>($kans) ; This will bring you the z-value</li><li>&sigma; = ($g - &mu;)/z</li><li>&sigma; = ($g - $mean)/$Z</li><li>So the standard deviation is $sigma</li></ul>
: <ul><li>$P(V &le; $g<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = $mean and &sigma; = <b>?</b> ) = $kans</li><li>Lookup in your table the probability closest to $kans</li><li>That should be $kans1</li><li>The corresponding z=$Z1</li><li>Use the formula z=(g - &mu; )/ &sigma; </li><li>So &sigma;=($g-&mu;)/$Z1</li><li>So the standard deviation is $sigma</li></ul>
