: Calculate, for the normal distributed variable <em>V</em> the standard deviation &sigma; when:<br />$P($g1 &lt; V &le; $g2<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = $mean and &sigma; = <b>?</b> ) = $kans 
: <ul><li>$P($g1 &lt; V &le; $g2<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = $mean and &sigma; = <b>?</b> ) = $kans</li><li>$g1 and $g2 are equal close to &mu; </li><li>$P(V &le; $g1  | &mu;=$mean ; &sigma;=<b>?</b> )=(1-$kans)/2=$kans2</li><li>input for  a TexasInstruments Ti83 &trade; graphical calculator <kbd>invNorm</kbd>($kans2) ;This will bring you the z-value</li><li>&sigma; = ($g - &mu;)/z</li><li>&sigma; = ($g - $mean)/$Z</li><li>So the standard deviation is $sigma</li></ul>
: <ul><li>$P($g1 &lt; V &le; $g2<b>&nbsp;|&nbsp;</b> &mu; = $mean and &sigma; = <b>?</b> ) = $kans</li><li>$g1 and $g2 are equal close to &mu; </li><li>$P(V &le; $g1  | &mu;=$mean ; &sigma;=<b>?</b> )=(1-$kans)/2=$kans2 <li>Lookup in your table the probability closest to $kans2 </li><li>That could be $kans1</li><li>The corresponding z=$Z1</li><li>Use the formula z = (g - &mu; )/ &sigma; </li><li>So &sigma; = ($g1 - $mean)/$Z1</li><li>So the standard deviation is  $sigma</li></ul>
: For the subject "<em>$vak</em>", students have to do a preliminaire test-exam,<br />that will prepare them for the official -real- exam in $vak .<br /> For the real exam the students answered $aantal exercises out of $totaal correct. <br />with a standard deviation of $m_sigma = $sigma .<br /> We assume the score to be normal distributed.<br />One student however states that the preliminary testexam was much easier than the real thing...<br />$zij performs a random check of $num students from all the students that took the official exam,<br /> $zij produces the next frequency table of the number of correctly answered questions in the preliminary test-exam,<br />this test-exam has also $totaal exercises.  <br /> $freqtabel <br />We assume the standard deviation of this test-exam to be  also $m_sigma = $sigma <br />What is the probability of this specific random check result, when the average is $aantal <b>?</b>  <br />So calculate the <b>p-value</b>
: <ul><li>The average of "correctly answered questions" is: $mean.</li><li>$P(X&ge;$mean)&asymp;$G</li><li>input for  a TexasInstruments Ti83 &trade; graphical calculator <kbd><b>normalcdf</b></kbd>( $mean , 10000000 , $aantal , $sigma/&radic;($num) )</li></ul> 
: <ul><li>The average of "correctly answered questions" is: $mean.</li><li>Calculate the <kbd>z-value</kbd> : z=($mean-$aantal)/($sigma/&radic;($num)) &asymp; $Z</li><li>Lookup the probability : $P(z&lt;$Z)&asymp;$[1-$G]</li><li>$P(X&ge;$mean)&asymp;$G</li></ul> 
